    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1958-07-18T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1958-07-18T13:00:00-05:00" n="29"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d29">
                <head>29. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in the United Kingdom</gloss>
                    to the <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d29fn0">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 440.002/7–1858. Confidential. Repeated to Brussels, The Hague, Bonn,
                        Rome, Luxembourg, and Paris.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>London</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1958-07-18T19:00:00+01:00">July 18, 1958, 7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>402. Luxembourg for <gloss target="#t_USEC1">USEC</gloss>. Paris pass <gloss
                        target="#t_USRO1">USRO</gloss>. In view absence <persName corresp="#p_LS1"
                        >Lloyd</persName> and preoccupation Prime Minister other matters, Department
                    circular telegram 33<note n="1" xml:id="d29fn1">
                        <ref target="#d26">Document 26</ref>.</note> and Department circular
                    telegram 58<note n="2" xml:id="d29fn2">In circular telegram 58, July 16, the
                        Department of State transmitted further instructions regarding the U.S.
                        position on <gloss target="#t_FTA1">FTA</gloss>. (Department of State,
                        Central Files, 440.002/7–1858)</note> conveyed <persName corresp="#p_MR1"
                        >Maudling</persName> today. He said will convey Chancellor. Following
                    summary his comments: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Agreed next two weeks crucial for <gloss target="#t_FTA1">FTA</gloss>
                            and appreciated continuing US support.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>
                            <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> will continue press for <gloss
                                target="#t_FTA1">FTA</gloss> and urge continuation negotiations.
                            Confirmed that report to <gloss target="#t_OEEC1">OEEC</gloss> Ministers
                            re failure carry out mandate would be in context request for new
                            instructions and time table. At ministerial meeting, <gloss
                                target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> will also seek reaffirmation support all
                                <gloss target="#t_OEEC1">OEEC</gloss> countries for <gloss
                                target="#t_FTA1">FTA</gloss>. (<persName corresp="#p_MR1"
                                >Maudling</persName> said <persName corresp="#p_PA1"
                                >Pinay</persName> expressed disbelief French had really agreed when
                            shown October 1957 <gloss target="#t_OEEC1">OEEC</gloss> resolution<note
                                n="3" xml:id="d29fn3">Presumably a reference to the <gloss
                                    target="#t_OEEC1">OEEC</gloss> Council resolution of October 17,
                                1957; see <ref target="#d8fn1">footnote 1, Document 8</ref>.</note>
                            and referred to <gloss target="#t_FTA1">FTA</gloss> as just <gloss
                                target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> device to stop common market.) Rumors
                            breakdown <gloss target="#t_FTA1">FTA</gloss> negotiations and loss
                                <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> interest have according <persName
                                corresp="#p_MR1">Maudling</persName>, had salutary effect in
                            stirring up Six.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>
                            <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> opposed to interim 10 percent tariff
                            cut on generalized basis because (A) no reciprocity seems possible; and
                            (B) would not be move toward <gloss target="#t_FTA1">FTA</gloss>. (This
                            in considerable part matter of principle—would represent common action
                            on external tariffs while fundamental to <gloss target="#t_FTA1"
                                >FTA</gloss> concept that only internal to be affected.) Stated
                            Benelux and Germany also opposed generalization. Would support 10
                            percent cut limited <gloss target="#t_OEEC1">OEEC</gloss> countries but
                            only as first step toward <gloss target="#t_FTA1">FTA</gloss> on which
                            real progress had been made of sort would justify US supporting <gloss
                                target="#t_GATT1">GATT</gloss> waiver. May suggest at <gloss
                                target="#t_CIG1">CIG</gloss> or ministerial meeting that
                            negotiations on provisional arrangement re 10 percent proceed along with
                            work on substance <gloss target="#t_FTA1">FTA</gloss>. <gloss
                                target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> would insist any provisional arrangement
                            apply to quotas as well as tariffs.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>With respect target for <gloss target="#t_FTA1">FTA</gloss> agreement, while not
                    concerned about gap of few months between common market action on internal
                    barriers <pb facs="0090" n="54" xml:id="pg_54"/> January 1, 1959 and similar
                        <gloss target="#t_FTA1">FTA</gloss>, provided progress being made toward
                        <gloss target="#t_FTA1">FTA</gloss>, feels longer delay would set trading
                    patterns and prejudice future of <gloss target="#t_FTA1">FTA</gloss>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_WJH1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Whitney</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
